    Key insights (per the agent prompt's "Key Insights" section):
      1. THIS PARTY EXTENDS THE POLYMORPHIC POC TO COMPLAINT CASES.
         Cases 03 and 05 (General Inquiry) have polymorphic party
         pairs (parties 01+02 on case 03, parties 04+05 on case 05);
         this party (with sibling party 07) brings the same pattern
         to a Complaint case (case 08). The UI Policy is case_type-
         agnostic, but having parties on BOTH case types proves the
         policy works identically across the General Inquiry and
         Complaint flows. This is the strongest evidence that the
         polymorphic single-table simplification of ArkCase's two-
         table association model (acm_person_assoc + acm_person_
         org_assoc) is functionally equivalent across the demo
         dataset's full case-type coverage.
      2. CASE 08 IS THE DENSEST EXEMPLAR. Critical priority + 2
         active tasks (06 In Progress, 07 Open) + 2 parties (THIS
         PARTY: Person/Requester, party 07: Organization/Respondent).
         Forms a complete polymorphic test case for the Complaint
         flow side: simultaneously exercising the transition rules,
         the task-closure resolve-blocker, and BOTH branches of the
         party-type polymorphism on a single parent case. Case 03
         plays the analogous role on the General Inquiry flow side
         (also Critical priority + 2 active tasks + 2 parties with
         party 01 as Person/Requester and party 02 as Organization/
         Respondent).
      3. DEMO MANAGER APPEARS ON CASES 03 AND 08. Both as Person
         Requester. This demonstrates that the SAME user can be a
         party on multiple cases - a real operational scenario where
         one individual files multiple complaints over time. The
         display_value "x_[scope]_demo_manager" lookup resolves to
         the same sys_user row on both files; the seed script's
         ensureUser() helper queries by user_name BEFORE inserting,
         so re-runs do NOT create duplicate demo manager rows. The
         agent prompt explicitly calls out this multi-case-membership
         pattern as a load-bearing demonstration of operational
         realism.
      4. THE DETERMINISTIC SYS_IDS ENSURE IDEMPOTENT RE-IMPORTS.
         Every party in this 8-party fixture uses MD5-derived sys_ids
         computed from canonical input strings. Re-running the agent
         rebuild always produces the same sys_ids; the Update Set
         XML is byte-identical across rebuilds; and the re-import
         preview gate (Validation Gate 7) reports zero changes when
         re-importing an already-applied Update Set. This party's
         sys_id is 0363ce9a22841161b5837af17f435f7f - distinct from
         every other demo party's sys_id by construction.
      5. PAIR WITH PARTY 07. This party (Person/Requester on case 08)
         and party 07 (Organization/Respondent on case 08) form the
         canonical dual-party Complaint exemplar. On the case-08
         form, the Related List shows BOTH parties; the polymorphic
         UI Policy renders this party with the person field visible
         and party 07 with the organization field visible -
         simultaneously, on the same case, in the same Related List.
         This is the strongest single demonstration of the
         polymorphic invariant working correctly on the Complaint
         flow.
      6. NO PII, `[scope]` PRESERVED. No real names, no real email
         addresses, no real phone numbers, no real organizational
         identifiers. The literal `[scope]` placeholder appears
         verbatim everywhere it is used; the PDI substitutes the
         concrete scope id at apply time.
-->
<record_update table="x_[scope]_case_party">
    <x_[scope]_case_party action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <case display_value="CASE0000008">CASE0000008</case>
        <organization/>
        <party_type>Person</party_type>
        <person display_value="x_[scope]_demo_manager">x_[scope]_demo_manager</person>
        <role_label>Requester</role_label>
        <sys_class_name>x_[scope]_case_party</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_id>0363ce9a22841161b5837af17f435f7f</sys_id>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>x_[scope]_case_party_demo_06</sys_update_name>
    </x_[scope]_case_party>
</record_update>
